{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2025-02-06T02:38:43.962630+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T17:41:37.779858+00:00", "id": 14818273, "conceptrecid": "14818272", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.14818273", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.14818272", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.14818273", "metadata": {"title": "Evolution and function of the upper molar talon and its dietary implications in microbats: FUNCTION OF THE TALON IN MICROBATS", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.14818273", "publication_date": "2015", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) The evolution of mammalian molars has been marked by transitions representing significant changes in shape and function. One such transition is the addition and elaboration of the talon, the distolingual region of the ancestral tribosphenic upper molar of therian mammals and some extinct relatives. This study uses suborder Microchiroptera as a case study to explore the adaptive implications of the expansion of the talon on the tribosphenic molar, specifically focusing on the talon's role in the compression and shear of food during breakdown. Three-dimensional computer renderings of casts of the upper left first molars were created for microbat species of a variety of dietary categories (frugivore, etc.) and physical properties of food (hard and soft). Relief Index (RFI) was measured to estimate the topography and function of the whole tooth and of the talon and trigon (the remaining primitive tribosphenic region) individually, in order to examine 1) how the shape of the whole tooth, trigon, and talon reflects the compromise between their crushing and shearing functions, 2) how whole tooth, trigon, and talon function differs according to diet, and 3) how the presence of the talon affects overall molar function. Results suggest that RFI of both the whole tooth and the trigon varies according to dietary groups, with frugivores having greater crushing function when compared with the other groups. The talon, however, consistently has low RFI (a flatter topography), and its presence lowers the RFI of the whole tooth across all dietary categories, suggesting that the talon is primarily functioning in crushing during food breakdown. The potential benefits of a crushing talon for microbats of various dietary groups are discussed. J. Morphol. 276:1368\u20131376, 2015. VC 2015 Wiley Periodicals, Inc.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Gutzwiller, Sarah C.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Hunter, John P.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/774497cc61667da1884a8962f9d6dfb3", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/585ca568cfb08f37068d5ba7155819e610d195e9559223851834a64696ef97b0", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/LKKZBYJS", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/LKKZBYJS", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/9ed6f6930523661357fab1f93fcf3dba!/b280696-283277", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "11", "pages": "1368-1376", "title": "Journal of Morphology", "volume": "276"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/774497cc61667da1884a8962f9d6dfb3"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:LKKZBYJS"}, {"identifier": "10.1002/